When I was a kid my family took a destination camping boating trip to Southern California. On the journey  home I was riding in the back of the pick-up truck with the dog (I know, but it was legal way back then and we were simple folk) as we were traveling we came across a road closure by the CHP. There were a half dozen cars already stacked in the line so naturally we thought it was simply an unfortunate accident (we'd seen a few on this trip already) or maybe a cigarette fire but after a few minutes the officer walked the line to inform the waiting drivers what the hold up was and to stay in their cars. There was a migration passing through. Being a kid and it being the early eighties, as I said before, I had been riding in bed of the truck and was able to ask the CHiPy what kind migration was passing through. As it turned out, the officer and his partner were among the first to come across the crawling mass, a matt of orange and black fur crossing the highway and they nearly crashed after squishing several of the unfortunate creatures. This of course prompted an emergency road closure. While we sat for about an hour waiting the swarm expanded and I looked down from the bed of our battered old blue Chevrolet to see that they had crawled around our truck, thousands of them harmlessly crossing the road. There was a biker who climbed onto the hood of the CHP cruiser, next to the officers while his three riding partners requested to sit in the boat we were towing. It's important to say here, that this was not a horror movie, not one tarantula climbed a car or in through the vents they didn't even try to climb the tires. The whole thing was hiss of rustling dry grasses and passed without further incident. I often thought I had dreamt the i this had happened, but a few years ago my mom confirmed to me, while we were relieving memories of my dad, that it had indeed happened. It  happened, it passed and there was no lasting sign it ever had. Surreal.

Apparently Curtis Yarvin and "Dark Enlightenment" is the whole philosophical framework behind the Trump administration.  Perplexity (Deep Research): "Who is Curtis Yarvin and what is his vision and values"  Curtis Yarvin, born in 1973, has emerged as one of the most controversial political thinkers in American discourse, known for founding the neo-reactionary movement and advocating for the replacement of democracy with monarchical governance. Also writing under the pen name Mencius Moldbug, Yarvin has cultivated significant influence among right-wing intellectuals, Silicon Valley technologists, and certain political figures within Republican circles. His ideas represent a radical departure from mainstream conservative thought, combining techno-utopianism with authoritarian governance models.  Yarvin is most prominently known for founding, along with philosopher Nick Land, the anti-egalitarian and anti-democratic philosophical movement known as the Dark Enlightenment or neo-reactionary movement (NRx). This philosophy fundamentally challenges the liberal democratic order that has dominated Western political thought since the Enlightenment.  The core of Yarvin's political vision centers on the rejection of democracy as a failed experiment. Through his blog Unqualified Reservations (2007-2014) and later newsletter Gray Mirror (started in 2020), he has consistently argued that American democracy is inherently flawed and should be replaced with an "accountable monarchy" that would function with governance structures similar to those of corporations. This vision represents a complete rethinking of modern governance based on hierarchical principles rather than democratic ones.  One of Yarvin's most influential concepts is what he terms "the Cathedral" â€“ his framework for understanding how power operates in liberal democratic societies. According to critics of his work, Yarvin incorrectly characterizes modern progressive institutions as "uncoordinated, decentralized, emergent" when evidence suggests they are actually "coordinated, centralized, purposeful". This concept has nonetheless been widely adopted within certain right-wing intellectual circles.  Yarvin's political values represent a radical departure from mainstream conservatism, embracing positions that many consider deeply problematic. Why do fascists lie?Â   By Stephen Kierein   They lie because the image of themselves is not the person they actually are. They need to lie, even to themselves. It is not by accident that politician and liar are widely agreed to be synonymous. A politician's entire career is built around pretending to be whatever others wish them to be and often has very little to do with who they truly are. Trump is a good example. He built a persona that he convinced people was his own. People who knew him privately knew him to be something completely different. His own blood agree he is a psychopathic narcissistic and incompetent megalomaniac. However, he fooled everyone into believing he was a top tier businessman and master negotiator with a godlike intellect never before seen in all the history of the world. Once people believe the lie, they can be controlled.   Fascism is exactly the same. Hitler was not seen as a monster by his own people BECAUSE he controlled the truth. Anyone who wishes to control the truth should never be trusted. A free press is designed to make truth completely separate from the controls of the powerful. So long as the powerful attempt to control the facts for their own ends, we will always be vulnerable to this kind of attack from within. Donald trump, or someone like him, will try to do this again. Do not fool yourself into thinking it could never happen. If the capitol building can be sacked, anything can happen. It is vitally important that we do something immediately to prevent this madness from repeating itself, and a doctorate could well be written on the myriad lessons we can take away from this civilization shaking cataclysm. There is a very good reason we are hardwired to be wary of those who lie. It provides a very real survival (dare I say evolutionary?) Advantage. Where politics is concerned, however, dishonesty is a fact of the game. Why ought the powerful get this kind of imbalance? Why did we build a system on a foundation of accepting the unacceptable?Â    We as a nation must ask ourselves this question. Unlike every other political issue, we MUST find solutions. The game is built to make solutions temporary and makes conflict the name of the game.Â    We say, "you are not to discuss race, religion, and politics in public!" But this is itself a damning demand. The damnation comes from the unspoken component. It comes from the answer to why you are not to talk about these things: to prevent conflict.   That answer admits to the asker that these beliefs should never be questioned if our civilization is to survive the night. These beliefs, which are not properly rooted in facts and evidence, are easy to disprove. However, the powerful have these beliefs to thank for the very existence of their power. That is why the powerful want exceptions. Without exceptions to the rules, legal or otherwise, the powerful would loose their power by the very act of preserving that power as this insurrection has underlined that point clearly.   The dishonest rely on objectively unethical practices like controlling who can and who cannot vote. We call this voter suppression. They call it election integrity steps. However, regardless what you call it, it is the same thing. You can do whatever mental gymnastics you want, but that fact will still remain after all of it. that fact cannot be overcome with facts, so we are expected to not bring it up. Its the same with most "political" issues.Â    Take abortion rights. The left and the right use different facts as their foundation in the same way that Christianity and Hinduism are founded on mutually exclusive sets of myths. Pointing at that makes the powerful unhappy, but they do not have to be happy; we do.Â    Please think on this, people. Our future hangs in the balance. Do not let it be cast to ruin by the greedy and the selfish.

I tend to agree, that voting should be a right. The question is, what about edge cases?  Should ex-convicts (people who have served prison time) still have the right to vote? Yes, I think so.  Should convicts (people who are currently serving time in prison) still have the right to vote? Yes, I think so, but I'm less certain.  In the event that someone gets caught committing a crime related to voting, suppose the person knowingly and intentionally voted at a wrong precinct, or voted multiple times, or impersonated someone to cast extra votes, etc? It would seem very reasonable to ban that person from voting, but then it starts to wobble toward being a privilege again.  And that's before we get into the question of "a right for whom?" Adult citizens of the states, absolutely, and, for me, even adult citizens of the territories should have the right to vote. (I'm going to set aside the question of what an "adult" is).  But what about permanent residents? If they have made America their home, shouldn't they have a say? I say yes, but the thing is, at least IMHO, that's a really hard question that could quite reasonably go the other way. And if we can decide whether to allow permanent residents to vote, it once again starts to feel more like a privilege we can give or take rather than a god-given right.  So, yeah, calling something a right is thorny.
